The Losers Remain Challengers
HARARE: Before the presidential elections this month, I was convinced that irregularities during the elections would have had serious consequences in Zimbabwe itself and throughout southern Africa.
Despite the shadows of war and terrorism, I called for fair and free elections.
The people of Zimbabwe did not receive them.
Instead, they received terror.
In the two years that have led up to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe were subjected to intimidation, harassment, and threats by the party of Robert Mugabe, the African National Union - Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose program is state-sponsored terrorism.
The ZANU terror is on the account of the scoundrels among the veterans of Zimbabwe's independence war two decades ago, government militias and young men, all of whom are supported by the police.
As a consequence of intimidation and violence, my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), failed to reach the electorate in wide areas, especially in rural areas.
Additionally, the government of my opponent, President Mugabe's, effectively disenfranchised hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, particularly in the capital city Harare and in Chitungwiza.
Since there were not enough polling stations, according to my opinion, more than 360,000 people in Harare and Chitungwiza alone stood in line without being able to cast their ballot into the ballot box.
I still doubt the legitimacy of the election result because Mugabe's militias prevented the MDC from deploying observers at 52% of rural polling stations.
At the end of the voting, our party was missing observers at 6 of 10 polling stations in the countryside.
This means that Mugabe's supporters were able to impose their will in these polling stations.
We are currently compiling a comprehensive list of all polling stations that were only controlled by ZANU supporters.
Even at this early stage, a systematic pattern has emerged in our investigations: in these polling stations, most votes were cast for Mugabe.
In view of the overwhelming evidence, I cannot accept the result of the presidential election, in which the incumbent President Robert Mugabe emerged as the winner with 56% of the 3 million cast votes.
The official result does not reflect the true will of the people of Zimbabwe and is, in their eyes, illegitimate.
The people of Zimbabwe were denied their right to elect a president of their choice freely and democratically.
The struggle for the election results is a political matter that must be resolved politically.
Food and fuel are scarce, jobs are lost, and inflation is over 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were brave and determined and deserve recognition for it.
Perhaps it is not too late yet.
I am writing this in distress, because Mugabe's regime still disregards the will of the people.
Whatever happens, I will stand by the people as a loyal servant and walk the path with them to the end.
I am possibly going to be arrested by the government.
I was even arrested for treason before the elections.
In the worst-case scenario, they even want to kill me.
But the government will never be able to break the will of the people, their rights, and their power.
It is in our hands to effect a democratic change.
In the coming days, we will experience moments of fear, but we must not allow ourselves to be overwhelmed by desperation.
The political change is unstoppable.
But we must be prepared to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his henchmen are afraid of the people, and we have heard that they will do everything to kill the messenger.
Should it come to that, I only ask the people of Zimbabwe to remain strong and to complete what we have begun together.
There are many heroes in the people of Zimbabwe - heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who were not driven away.
They are the heroes of a new Zimbabwe, whose voice must be heard in the world.
We have walked a very rocky road together to achieve a democratic change in our country.
In the history of humanity, a people have rarely had to endure such violence and still manage to maintain kindness and exuberance.
I notice that the people of Zimbabwe are impatient.
I understand that.
But for there to be a political process, they must be patient and wait.
They cannot leave these elections as they are, but they must not fall into Mugabe's provocation and resort to violence either.
The people of Zimbabwe want change, in the constitution, in the legal system, legitimate change, and they will achieve it, despite all obstacles.
We know that we are not standing alone.
We know that in all of Africa, people are betrayed during elections.
In the majority of African states, it seems that irregularities, cheating, and swindling are part of the elections.
In Africa, there is always a crisis somewhere due to elections.
It is sad, but the whole continent is plagued by governments that resort to unfair means when it's time to grant the people their right to vote.
But those who want something else can hope.
Zimbabwe's fight is not yet over.
There is still time to draw lessons from our experience for Africa and the world.
My people are in their greatest hour of need.
I pledge not to leave them.
